article.headline: Jacksonville 71, Tennessee Tech 67
article.story: JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Haminin Quaintance scored on a driving slam dunk with 28.3 seconds left to give Jacksonville its final lead in a come-from-behind 71-67 win over Tennessee Tech late Monday. Tech's Willie Jenkins had given the Golden Eagles a 67-66 lead by making one of two free throws with 50 seconds left, breaking the last of four tied scores in the final four minutes. Quaintance, who led the Dolphins with 21 points, took a pass from Aubrey Conerly and jammed home the basket while getting fouled. He missed the free throw and Jacksonville missed two more free throws in the next 10 seconds. Tech's Cameron Crisp was fouled with 3.4 seconds left, but missed the first free throw and intentionally missed the second. Jacksonville (5-3) got the rebound and salted the victory with a pair of free throws by Riley Didion with 2.6 seconds remaining. Jenkins led Tennessee Tech (5-5) with a game-high 25 points. Jacksonville trailed by as many as 14 points in the first half but closed to 40-32 at halftime. Quaintance finished with his second double-double of the year, adding a game-high 15 rebounds.
